title: Aust bonds mixed as Greece focus fades
text:
Fri, Jul 17, 2015, 4:51 PM AEST - Australia Markets closed Aust bonds mixed as Greece focus fades AAP â€“ 8 minutes ago Print 
The Australian bond market is mixed with little change as the Greek debt crisis fades from focus. 
IG chief market strategist Chris Weston said the bond market was continuing to trade in a tight range amid a lack of domestic data. 
"Traders have generally sat on their hands today - there hasn't been a lot of drivers," he said. 
"For now (Greece) seems to be on the backburner." 
Overnight, eurozone ministers approved the launch of Greece bailout talks and the ECB boosted its cash lifeline to the crisis-hit country after MPs in Athens grudgingly passed a tough reform package demanded by creditors. 
Investors will now focus on US inflation data for June due out Friday night. 
At 1630 AEST on Friday, the September 2015 10-year bond futures contract was trading at 97.005 (implying a yield of 2.995 per cent), up from 96.985 (3.015 per cent) on Thursday. 
The September 2015 three-year bond futures contract was at 97.970 (2.030 per cent), down from 97.980 (2.020 per cent). 
KEY MOVEMENTS: 
* CGS 5.5pct Jan 2018, 1.963%, from 1.951% on Thursday 
* CGS 4.25pct April 2026, 3.036%, from 3.057% 
Sydney Futures Exchange prices: 
* September 2015 bill futures, 97.890 from 97.900 
* December 2015 bill futures, 97.930, unchanged 
(*Closes taken at 1630 AEST previous local session) 
Source: IRESS
